<div id="review_1368377578" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1368377578" />
    <a title="Tadiana ✩Night Owl☽" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/8734459-tadiana-night-owl"><img alt="Tadiana ✩Night Owl☽" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1623779706p2/8734459.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1368377578?book_show_action=true">Aug 19, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Tadiana ✩Night Owl☽" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Tadiana ✩Night Owl☽" href="/user/show/8734459-tadiana-night-owl">Tadiana ✩Night Owl☽</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/8734459-tadiana-night-owl?shelf=gutenberg-freebie">gutenberg-freebie</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/8734459-tadiana-night-owl?shelf=victorian">victorian</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/8734459-tadiana-night-owl?shelf=mystery">mystery</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/8734459-tadiana-night-owl?shelf=dated-social-attitudes">dated-social-attitudes</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1368377578" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7362499631253922055">“How often have I said to you that when you have eliminated the impossible, whatever remains, however improbable, must be the truth?” <br/><br/><img src='https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1441336345i/16096120._SY540_.png' width='250' height='390' alt='description' class='gr-hostedUserImg'/><br/><br/>Only a week after reading the far more memorable <a href='https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/8921.The_Hound_of_the_Baskervilles__Sherlock_Holmes___5_' title='The Hound of the Baskervilles (Sherlock Holmes, #5) by Arthur Conan Doyle' rel='nofollow noopener'>Hound of the Baskervilles</a>, I could barely remember what “The Sign of Four” was about. It&apos;s mostly pleasant but forgettable.<br/><br/>In Sherlock Holmes&apos; second outing with Dr. Watson, Sherlock explains that he needs to shoot up cocaine and morphine to add spice to his life (apparently these were legal drugs at the time). Wats</span>
  <span id="freeText7362499631253922055" style="display:none">“How often have I said to you that when you have eliminated the impossible, whatever remains, however improbable, must be the truth?” <br><br><img src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1441336345i/16096120._SY540_.png" width="250" height="390" alt="description" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br><br>Only a week after reading the far more memorable <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/8921.The_Hound_of_the_Baskervilles__Sherlock_Holmes___5_" title="The Hound of the Baskervilles (Sherlock Holmes, #5) by Arthur Conan Doyle" rel="nofollow noopener">Hound of the Baskervilles</a>, I could barely remember what “The Sign of Four” was about. It's mostly pleasant but forgettable.<br><br>In Sherlock Holmes' second outing with Dr. Watson, Sherlock explains that he needs to shoot up cocaine and morphine to add spice to his life (apparently these were legal drugs at the time). Watson chastises Sherlock (unsuccessfully) for taking chances with his mind, and then distracts him with a question about his old pocket watch. Sherlock, true to form, dazzles the good Dr. Watson once again with his deductions. But this only occupies them for a few minutes. <br><br>Luckily for everyone except Holmes' drug supplier, Miss Mary Morstan arrives on the doorsteps of 221B Baker Street with a better distraction: a puzzle about a decade-long missing father and a mysterious annual gift of valuable pearls that she's been receiving from an unknown source for the past six years. Could these two mysteries possibly be related? <br><br>Holmes is intrigued; Watson is in instalove.<br><br>This is a reasonably good Sherlock Holmes novella, marred by some period racism toward Africans and a too-lengthy flashback toward the end that explains the mystery.<br><br>And now I have to go rewatch the Sherlock episode "The Sign of Three" and see what cool connections may exist to the plot of this book.<br><br><img src="https://images.gr-assets.com/hostedimages/1441320431ra/16092662.gif" width="300" height="315" alt="description" class="gr-hostedUserImg"> <br><br>September 2015 buddy read with the Pantsless Crunchy Bunch.</span>
  <a data-text-id="7362499631253922055" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


